direct_answer.text:
Let P be one endpoint of both curves so it lies above the origin since neither curve passes through it. Let Q also lie below the other intersection of our circles and let R and S each approach the corresponding intersections as close as possible without touching them along lines parallel to OP. APOSQ forms a right triangle while CPOR forms another because PSR is vertical too. As such, angles POQ=POA and PRS=PSO . Because SO equals SP but angle ORS plus angle OSP equal 180 degrees , line segment SR bisects OS making NSOQ a rectangle whose diagonals intersect at K inside square NOPQSU ..... [asy]
